**How My ASL (assessment in speaking and listening) becomes ASL(aesthetic standards level)**

When CBSE introduced the Assessment of Speaking and Listening (ASL), the idea was clear — evaluate students’ communication skills, their ability to present ideas, and their understanding of a topic. The purpose was to focus on content, language, and delivery, not on handwriting style or decorative borders.


**BUT HERE IS THE CATCH**
my recent experience, this purpose was overshadowed by unnecessary emphasis on presentation aesthetics.

**The Rise of the “Toxic Criteria”**

What happened to me is a perfect example of how ASL’s real purpose gets twisted.
Instead of judging content, communication skills, and understanding of the topic, the evaluation turned into an “Aesthetic Standards Level” competition. My teacher directly compared my work to some girls’ ASL projects, saying mine wasn’t “decorative enough” — as if neat handwriting and solid research mean nothing without glitter pens and fancy borders.

This is a toxic criteria system:

1. It promotes looks over learning.
2. It pressures students to spend more time decorating than researching.
3. It creates bias, because not everyone has the time, resources, or interest in making “art project” style assignments.


CBSE never said “Your marks depend on how pretty your margins are.” This is an unofficial, unfair, and demotivating standard that hurts students who focus on the actual skill — speaking and learning, not drawing and decorating.


**According to CBSE guidelines**, ASL (Assessment of Speaking and Listening) is judged on communication skills — like fluency, coherence, pronunciation, grammar accuracy, and vocabulary. Listening is tested separately. For written submissions, neatness and organization matter, but there is no official requirement for decoration, borders, or colored pens. My work met the real CBSE criteria, yet it was rejected only for not being “decorated,” which is not part of the official assessment system.


**My Actual Submission**

 Below is the exact content I submitted for my ASL. It was written by me, researched from reliable sources, and addressed the topic given to me (“Importance of Media”). It covered the definition, types, importance in daily life, media in education and youth life, entertainment+negetive sides, conclusion+personal opinion 
 

" **ASL Presentation**

Topic: Importance of Media
Name: BRO_BESTIE15
Class: 10 
Roll No: *****


---

**Introduction & Types of Media**

Good morning respected teacher and my dear friends,
Today I am going to speak on the topic “Importance of Media.”

Media is something that we all use in our daily life, maybe without even thinking about it. From watching news to scrolling Instagram, everything is media. It is basically the way information and entertainment is shared with people.

There are many types of media:

Print media like newspapers, books, and magazines.

Electronic media like TV and radio.

Digital media like websites, apps, YouTube, Instagram, and even WhatsApp.

Social media is also a part of digital media where we share and connect.



---

**Importance in Daily Life**

Media helps us stay connected with the world. We know about events happening in other countries, sports updates, weather news, and even local happenings because of media.

It also gives voice to the public. People can express opinions and support movements. During emergencies, like natural disasters or COVID-19 lockdown, media helped in spreading awareness fast.

Without media, the world would feel very small and disconnected.


---

**Media in Education and Youth Life**

For students, media is super helpful. We can watch educational videos on YouTube, use apps like BYJU’S, Unacademy, or Google to search topics we don’t understand. It is like having a digital teacher with us all the time.

Social media also has educational pages that explain news, science, current affairs etc. in a fun way. It’s not only books that teach us — media plays a big role too.

Many students get career guidance and motivation through podcasts, blogs, and interviews of successful people they see online. So media is not just timepass — it can build our future too.


--
**Entertainment + Negative Sides**

Of course, media also gives us entertainment. We watch movies, listen to songs, play online games, and chill with YouTube or memes. After studies, it helps to relax and refresh the mind.

But at the same time, media has some bad sides.

Some news is fake or one-sided

Social media can be addictive

People face cyberbullying or trolling

Too much media can waste time or distract from studies


That’s why we should use media carefully and not blindly believe everything we see or read.


---

**Conclusion + Opinion**

In conclusion, I would say media is a very powerful tool. It can inform, educate, and entertain us. It connects people and brings the world closer.

But like every tool, it depends on how we use it. If we use media in a smart and positive way, it can make us more aware and intelligent.

In my opinion, students like us should use media for learning, growing, and staying aware — not only for entertainment. We should also be careful about fake content and focus more on the real facts.



---

